<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0815-B"><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>With a 55-seat majority in the 100-member chamber, Republicans have enough votes to confirm Brown unless they break ranks.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Democrats responded by saying the filibuster is a hallowed tool that protects minority rights.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>In contrast to the previous days, debate on the Senate floor had a desultory air Friday, as senators saved their remaining ammunition for the coming week.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., once a self-described &quot;qualified supporter&quot; of Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist's efforts to force a vote on the judges, announced in the second day of heated debate that his is now an &quot;unqualified&quot; backer of Frist.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>In a Gallup poll released Monday, just 22 percent of respondents said they have &quot;a great deal&quot; or &quot;quite a lot&quot; of confidence in Congress -- the lowest rating since 1997 and down from 30 percent last year.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>It takes 60 votes to end debate in the 100-seat chamber.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>Frist noted that she was the daughter of an Alabama sharecropper.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>It was unclear how the proposed accord would handle the seven pending Bush nominees.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Before filing the motion, Sen. John Cornyn, R-Texas, accused Democrats of exaggerating when they call the dispute a &quot;constitutional crisis.&quot;</line><line>Cheney is expected to rule in favor of Frist, and Democratic leader Harry Reid, D-Nev., is expected to object.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Optional add follows.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>&quot;It is a sad day for the Senate - and for Americans who are counting on senators to fulfill their constitutional duty to evaluate every judicial nominee carefully and confirm only those who will uphold Americans' constitutional rights and legal protections,&quot; said Ralph Neas, president of People For The American Way, the group most active in opposing her nomination.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Her advocates praise her rulings as no-nonsense while opponents characterize them as hostile to families and women.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>&quot;And I hope that in the coming days, we will complete our debate and resolve the controversy in a respectful manner, consistent with the greatest traditions of the United States Senate.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Frist said the dispute was really about Senatorial responsibility.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Those steps, commonly referred to as the &quot;nuclear option&quot; in the Senate dispute, would result in the Senate's rules being changed so that a simple majority vote of 51 senators would be enough to prevent filibusters of judicial nominees.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>The result of Cheney's ruling, followed by the three votes, would be to establish a new parliamentary procedure for considering judicial nominations that would bypass a cloture vote to end debate, thereby making the filibuster useless as a stalling static.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Reid had previously warned that if the Republican majority push the &quot;nuclear&quot; parliamentary button, Democrats would stall all but the most essential legislation in the Senate.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>On the Senate floor Wednesday, GOP leaders charged that Democrats have abused the filibuster by using it on several judicial nominations, which they said was not a part of Senate traditions.</line><line>When he spoke of killing nominees, however, Democratic Whip Richard Durbin, Ill., hurried to the floor and admonished Frist to &quot;choose words carefully.&quot;</line><line>Aides familiar with the negotiations said they focused on two issues: the fate of seven pending appellate court nominees who were blocked from an up or down vote in Bush's first term, and the more difficult issue of agreeing on how Democrats would treat the right to filibuster judicial nominees in coming months, when a Supreme Court vacancy might occur.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Those talks took place in the privacy of Senate offices in contrast to the public debate on the Senate floor that seemed to become more heated by the hour, each side accusing the other of political motives well beyond the sole judicial nominee under consideration, Priscilla Owen of Texas.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>&quot;Referencing Hitler was meant to dramatize the principle of an argument, not to characterize my Democratic colleagues,&quot; Santorum said, in a statement.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Under a filibuster, a determined minority can keep a measure or a nomination from being approved if it can muster 41 votes against.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Another sign of the hardening of positions came late in the afternoon Thursday when Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., chairman of the Republican Conference, the No. 3 job in the leadership, invoked Adolph Hitler in his criticism of Democrats.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>&quot;That's too bad.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Story can end here.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>But the Republican push to ban the filibuster for judicial nominees has become known as the nuclear option because of the partisan discord it would spark in the Senate.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>&quot;I would hope that today the filibuster would not be used to deny an up-or-down vote on Janice Rogers Brown, because every parent deserves to dream for every child that they'll have a chance...,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050608.0153"><line>Majority Leader Bill Frist, whose bid to strip Democrats of their use of the filibuster on judges was undercut by moderates, praised the confirmation of Brown, saying, &quot;Principle has won a victory over partisan judicial obstruction.&quot;<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="20"><scu uid="16" label="Nuclear option would have forced a change in filibuster rules" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>At the same time, Frist would not have the 51 votes he needs to disallow filibusters of judicial nominations.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, R-Tenn., on Monday said Brown, the first black woman to serve on the California Supreme Court, rose to the top of the legal profession through &quot;great achievement and great talent.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Democrats are attempting to thwart a confirmation vote of her because they view her as an &quot;extremist&quot; conservative.</line><line>Republicans say using the filibusters on so many nominees is unprecedented and breaks 200 years of tradition.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="31"/></line><line>In return, Republicans would pledge not to lend their votes to the effort to change the filibuster rules, unless at some point they think the Democrats had violated the spirit of the agreement.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="33"><scu uid="11" label="CA - Filibuster rules will remain unchanged" weight="4"/></annotation></line><line>&quot;This oncoming train wreck is bad for the Senate, it is bad for the country, it is bad for the Democrats and it is bad for the Republicans,&quot; he said on the Senate floor.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>Brown, 55, a member of the California Supreme Court, won confirmation after nearly two years of efforts by Democrats to deny her a lifetime appointment to the federal bench, contending that she has ignored legal precedents with rulings that promote an ultra-conservative political agenda.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Despite behind-the-scenes efforts at compromise, partisan lines deepened in the Senate's historic debate over judicial nominees Thursday as a Republican who had advocated finding a middle ground lined up behind the GOP's leadership and both parties injected racial politics into the fight.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>&quot;And you'll see it today; you'll see it tomorrow, you'll see it the next day.&quot;</line><line>They accused her of infusing her court decisions with conservative ideology and opposing most forms of government regulation.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050524.0295"><line>Republicans had accused Democrats of unprecedented obstruction, but Democrats said the nominees were too conservative to decide on social and cultural issues.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>When the Republicans objected, Durbin said their actions made it &quot;clear that this is not about judges&quot; but rather &quot;a power grab&quot; by the president and his Republican allies in the Senate.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>By ending debate on Pryor's nomination, the Senate set the stage for his confirmation as well, probably Thursday, the last confirmation vote guaranteed under an agreement reached by the &quot;Gang of 14&quot; senators from both parties to avoid a potentially damaging fight over the Senate's rules on debate.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Frist's appearance at the news conference followed his refusal to meet with members of the Congressional Black Caucus, a group of House Democrats who told Frist in a letter that a ban on judicial filibusters &quot;would be particularly offensive to people of color.&quot;</line><line>How dare you invade me.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>But Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid, D-Nev., charged that the threatened attempt to change the Senate's rules is part of &quot;a power grab&quot; by the Republican majority of the Senate, in league with the Bush White House and the GOP-controlled House of Representatives.</line><line>Gonzales once called Owen's judicial activism &quot;unconscionable.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>They were joined by three other centrist Democrats in voting to cut off the debate on Brown: Sen. Thomas Carper of Delaware, Sen. Kent Conrad of North Dakota, and Sen. Bill Nelson of Florida.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Such an arrangement would effectively end the crisis because Democrats would not have the votes they need to prevent votes on the nominees in question.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>It's going to work with William Pryor.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Then Democrats filibustered 10 of Bush's nominees, seven of which have been renominated.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Four Democrats and eight Republicans met privately in the office of Sen. John Warner, R-Va., seeking a deal of some kind, but the meeting concluded only with an agreement to reconvene Thursday.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>There are a lot of issues to consider,&quot; Snowe told reporters.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>The fate of two other circuit court nominees -- William Myers to the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco, and Henry Saad to the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Detroit -- was not addressed by the moderates' compromise and remains uncertain.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line><line>Brown is expected to be the second long-stalled judge confirmed after a bipartisan group of maverick and traditionalist senators cut their own deal last month to break an impasse over confirming President Bush's picks for the federal courts.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>Frist said that, &quot;After being delayed for two years by partisan obstruction (Brown's nomination) will finally get an up-or-down vote, which she deserves.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>&quot;I don't know if I've ever known a more activist member of the judiciary, anyplace.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Democrats argued that the conservative views and judicial activism of Owen and California Supreme Court Justice Janice Rogers Brown, whose nomination is next up on the Senate calendar, are beyond the mainstream of legal thinking in the United States.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="36"><scu uid="32" label="Democrats deemed Brown an extreme conservative ideologue" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Urging moderate Republicans to join the Democrats in opposing Frist, Kerry said, &quot;The Senate and the country need senators who are prepared to make their mark on history by standing with past profiles in courage, and defending not party, not partisanship, but defending principle and democracy itself.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050608.0153"><line>Indeed, Republicans can claim a victory by forcing a vote and confirming three judicial nominees adamantly opposed by Democrats and considered by liberals to be too ideologically conservative.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>&quot;It's 200 years of tradition and precedent.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>The arguments were familiar ones concerning Brown.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, R-Tenn., demanded an up-or-down vote on one of President Bush's more controversial judicial nominees Wednesday, sparking an historic Senate floor debate that could be the most consequential of Bush's presidency.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="11"/></line><line>Frist brought Texas Supreme Court Justice Priscilla Owen's nomination to the Senate floor, setting the Senate on a course toward a showdown vote as early as next week on changing its rules and traditions to make it easier to confirm judicial nominees.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>But when Republicans took control of the Senate during the Clinton presidency, &quot;we exacerbated the pattern of delay and blocking nominations,&quot; Specter said, by pushing the average duration to 192 days for district court nominees and 262 days for circuit court nominees.</line><line>Majority Leader Bill Frist, R-Tenn., set the tone with an opening speech that said Democrats want to &quot;kill, to defeat, to assassinate these nominees.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>Bush renominated her earlier this year.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Some Republicans are trying to convince Democrats that, even if every pending judge were given an up-or-down vote, it isn't a foregone conclusion all seven would be confirmed.</line><line>&quot;I think there will be an uproar on our side if we throw anybody overboard,&quot; Hatch said.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050524.0295"><line>The Republicans, for their parts, said they would oppose any attempt to make changes in the application of filibuster rules.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Bush first nominated Owen in 2001, but Democrats have blocked four attempts by the Republican majority to bring her nomination to a confirmation vote.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="14,19,44,48"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050524.0016"><line>There is &quot;no commitment to vote for or against&quot; the filibuster against two other conservative nominees, Henry Saad and William Myers.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Republican negotiators included Olympia Snowe, Maine; John McCain, Ariz.; Mike DeWine, Ohio; John Warner, Va.; Lindsey Graham, S.C.; and Lisa Murkowski, Alaska.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Owen, a member of the Texas Supreme Court since 1994, has a high rating from the American Bar Association.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>Fifty-one percent of respondents said they have &quot;some&quot; confidence, and 26 percent said they have &quot;very little&quot; or &quot;none.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>&quot;Such a deal on confirmations would only confirm public cynicism about what goes on in Washington behind closed doors,&quot; Specter said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>Before the vote, members of the Congressional Black Caucus walked into the Senate to demonstrate their opposition to Brown.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>And he made it clear he is prepared to take extraordinary parliamentary steps to stop the Democrats.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>The Senate vote clears the way for Brown to take a seat on the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia, one of 12 courts of appeal in the federal judiciary, but the only one with special jurisdiction over legal challenges arising from decisions and rules of federal agencies located in Washington.</line><line>The Senate voted 56-43 to elevate conservative California jurist Janice Rogers Brown to the nation's most important federal appeals court Wednesday, the second of President Bush's controversial nominees to win confirmation under a special agreement between centrist Republicans and Democrats.<annotation scu-count="5" sum-count="8" sums="14,23,25,29,41,44,51,55"><scu uid="6" label="Compromise agreement (CA) was reached " weight="4"/><scu uid="40" label="Brown won confirmation" weight="4"/><scu uid="41" label="Brown won confirmation 56-43" weight="3"/><scu uid="42" label="Brown won confirmation on June 8, 2005" weight="3"/><scu uid="2" label="Senators [centrist bipartisan] group kept working on possible compromises" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Democrats have used the filibuster threat to block 10 of Bush's appellate court nominees during his first term.</line><line>Six Republicans and six Democrats are discussing a draft agreement under which Democrats would pledge not to use the filibuster in the future, except under &quot;extraordinary circumstances.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>&quot;The president has rights (to appoint judges of his choice)... and we have a job to do.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>These radical judges don't deserve the attention that these other issues do.&quot;</line><line>Her father also spent much of his career in the Air Force.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Their criticism now of Republican efforts to change the rules on debating judicial nominees is &quot;the equivalent of Adolph Hitler in 1942 saying, 'I'm in Paris.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>&quot;This whole legislative year, we have yet to spend a single minute debating health care, debating education, debating the environment, debating the things that people in America feel important,&quot; Reid said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050608.0153"><line>A vote on him is expected Thursday or Friday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Republicans countered the criticism of the two women by noting that both had won overwhelming majorities in their elections to the state courts on which they sit - 84 percent for Owen, 76 percent for Brown.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050524.0295"><line>It was expected to vote for her confirmation later in the day.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Senate aides said that debate on Monday would begin in the afternoon and could last deep into the night.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>&quot;It's not her life that I attack when I say I'm not for Janice Rogers Brown.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>At that point, Frist would ask senators to vote on whether to proceed to a final confirmation vote, which would likely pass, and then he would ask senators to vote on Owen's confirmation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>When Frist declined his proposal to adjourn the Senate debate to the privacy of the old Senate chambers in the Capitol - a two-story antiquated amphitheater abandoned by the Senate in 1859 - Reid fired what may have been a political warning shot: he denied what is normally routine unanimous consent to let committees meet more than two hours after the Senate begins its session.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Democrats say the president's decision to renominate so many judges unacceptable to them is unprecedented.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>At a separate news conference in the Hart Senate office building, Rev. Timothy McDonald, chairman of the African American Ministers in Action (AAMIA), disputed suggestions that racism and sexism are behind opposition to Brown and Owen.</line><line>While Democrats are entitled to oppose Owen's nomination to a seat on the New Orleans-based 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, Frist said, &quot;they should not hide behind a procedure that prevents 100 United States senators from their responsibility, their duty to vote 'yes' or 'no' on the nominee.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>If all Democrats and independent James Jeffords, Vt., voted against a nominee, six Republicans would have to join them -- or 11 Republicans would have to be absent -- for the nomination to fail in the Senate, where Republicans hold 55 seats.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>And the senators would call on the White House to consult with the chamber in advance of submitting nominations, especially those to the Supreme Court.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>First nominated to the federal appeals court for the District of Columbia by Bush in 2003, she was among several presidential choices Democrats blocked through filibuster threats during his first term.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>The &quot;six and six&quot; proposal, as it is called, would obligate Democratic signatories to forswear backing a filibuster against future judicial nominees except in extraordinary circumstances.</line><line>&quot;We need to clear it up,&quot; said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.</line><line>Staff writers Dan Balz and Spencer S. Hsu contributed to this report.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>&quot;Elections have consequences,&quot; Smith said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>In a floor speech, Judiciary Chairman Arlen Specter, R-Pa., traced the politicization of the confirmation process to 1987, when Democrats took over the Senate and the confirmation rate for Circuit Court nominees fell to 65 percent from 89 percent earlier in the Reagan administration.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>&quot;The Senate has set a standard for fairness with Janice Rogers Brown and we expect the same for the remaining judicial nominees,&quot; said Tony Perkins, president of Family Research Council, a Washington organization that has rallied evangelical Christians to the cause of confirming Bush's nominees.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>And when the Democrats, for the second day, invoked a rule to limit the work of committees while the Senate is in session, Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., the assistant GOP leader, charged that the minority with &quot;unprecedented obstructionism.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="19"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Gonzales, in a brief meeting with reporters last week, down played his past criticism of Owen and said he wholeheartedly endorsed her federal court nomination.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>&quot;We look pretty silly lecturing Iraq on how to set up a government when we can't even decide on having an up-or-down vote on President Bush's judicial nominees.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050524.0016"><line>Averting a showdown, centrists from both parties reached agreement on a compromise that clears the way for confirmation votes on many of President George W. Bush's stalled judicial nominees, leaves others in limbo and preserves Senate filibuster rules.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="6" sums="11,14,20,33,40,44"><scu uid="6" label="Compromise agreement (CA) was reached " weight="4"/><scu uid="11" label="CA - Filibuster rules will remain unchanged" weight="4"/><scu uid="14" label="CA - Vote for cloture on three nominations " weight="3"/><scu uid="2" label="Senators [centrist bipartisan] group kept working on possible compromises" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>Following Brown, three more judicial nominations are on the Senate docket for action this week: Alabama Attorney General William Pryor, nominated for the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta, and Richard Griffin and David McKeague, both of Michigan and both nominated to the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Detroit.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>Republicans have responded to such criticism by accusing Democrats of unfairly using the filibuster to thwart Bush and a GOP-controlled Senate from filling vacancies on the federal bench.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>It is working with Janice Rogers Brown.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="6"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>A vote to end debate on Brown, known as &quot;cloture,&quot; is expected Tuesday, and Brown's confirmation vote could come as early as Wednesday.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>The Tennessee Republican was referring to the Democrats' use of unlimited debate, or the filibuster, to stall a confirmation vote on 10 of Bush's appellate court nominees in the last Congress.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>The White House is taking the position that it wants no compromise and is insisting on an up or down vote on each of its nominees.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>Gallup said Congress ranks with big business and organized labor among 15 institutions tested, and only slightly better than the lowest-rated institution, health maintenance organizations.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>First, Majority Leader Bill Frist, R-Tenn., would ask Cheney for a ruling on whether senators should have a right to vote on whether to proceed to a confirmation vote.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>Congressional approval ratings have plummeted this spring, and Democrats have charged that the Republican-controlled Senate has spent too much time on Bush's judicial nominees instead of dealing with the country's problems.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>As the debate raged on the Senate floor, moderate senators continued to search for a compromise that would avoid a showdown over the filibuster rule and the half-dozen Bush judicial nominees that Democrats have blocked.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>But appointing judges who will use their powerful positions to issue rulings that hurt women and racial minorities will not solve the problem.&quot;</line><line>Scott Shepard's e-mail address is sshepard@coxnews.com.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>The Senate ended the filibuster of California Supreme Court Justice Janice Rogers Brown Tuesday when 10 Democrats crossed party lines and voted to close debate, clearing the way for a confirmation vote Wednesday on her nomination to the second-most powerful court in the country.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="8" sums="11,25,29,41,43,49,51,55"><scu uid="33" label="Senate passed cloture to end Brown's debate" weight="4"/><scu uid="34" label="Brown's cloture vote was on June 7/8, 2005" weight="3"/></annotation></line><line>&quot;It worked with Priscilla Owen.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050524.0295"><line>Under the deal, Democrats agreed to vote for cloture, or an end to debate, for three judicial nominees: Janice Rogers Brown, William Pryor and Owen.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="4" sums="19,37,57,6"><scu uid="6" label="Compromise agreement (CA) was reached " weight="4"/><scu uid="14" label="CA - Vote for cloture on three nominations " weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>There was no immediate response from the Democratic leadership, but the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee (DSCC) posted a video of Santorum's remarks on the Internet shortly after he left the Senate floor.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050608.0153"><line>That will matter most if there is a vacancy on the Supreme Court, a possibility widely seen as likely given the serious illness of Chief Justice William Rehnquist.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Hatch, along with other conservative GOP senators, doesn't want to compromise if it means choosing which nominees would be approved and which rejected.</line><line>Warner hosted at least one meeting.</line><line>The first President Bush's lower court nominees took an average of 100 days to confirm, twice the average duration under the Carter administration.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>The second day of debate opened in the Senate with Sen. Dick Durbin, D-Ill., the assistant Democratic leader, proposing that the Senate set aside Owen's nomination temporarily to allow a vote on four other judicial nominees awaiting a confirmation vote.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>The Senate opened a long-awaited debate on whether to ban filibusters of judicial nominees Wednesday with vividly partisan attacks, as a small group of moderates worked behind the scenes for a compromise to avert the showdown.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="48"><scu uid="2" label="Senators [centrist bipartisan] group kept working on possible compromises" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>He cited the appearance Wednesday morning before the Senate Judiciary Committee of U.S. District Court Judge Joan Lefkow, whose husband and mother were recently murdered.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Although Frist did not mention Brown's race, the Senate majority leader said the Democratic treatment of her nomination was &quot;uncivil&quot; and he vowed that he will &quot;do everything in my power to see that it stops.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>The Democrats recalled some of the criticism U.S. Attorney General Alberto Gonzales leveled at Owen when they were colleagues on the Texas Supreme Court.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>&quot;It was a mistake and I meant no offense.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>It is a confrontation of &quot;mutually assured destruction,&quot; he added.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050524.0295"><line>The Senate voted 81-18 to end the filibuster over the nomination of Texas Supreme Court justice Priscilla Owen to a federal judgeship.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="13,19,43,48,57"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>&quot;Right now, the only check on President Bush is the Democrats' ability to voice their concern in the Senate,&quot; Reid said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>Democrats had blocked a confirmation vote on Brown since November 2003 by refusing to end debate, a tactic known as the filibuster.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="32,43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>The radical right wing will be free to pursue any agenda they want.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Santorum said Democrats broke Senate rules with their filibusters of judicial nominees two years ago.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="13,49,51,57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Sources said Saad had made too many Democratic enemies, in part by accidentally sending a senator an e-mail that criticized the lawmaker.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>Bush nominated Brown to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia, the main appeals court for government-related litigation.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="13,43"><scu uid="25" label="Brown's nomination was to the US District Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>(Begin optional trim)</line><line>Stakes are especially high this year, senators say, as many expect the first Supreme Court vacancy in more than a decade.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050524.0295"><line>Democrats blocked 10 of Bush's 218 nominees in his first term by using filibuster.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Frist set the heated tone of daylong debate when he accused Democrats of using obstructionist tactics &quot;to kill, to defeat, to assassinate&quot; a handful of Bush nominees to federal appellate courts.</line><line>Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, sought to shift the debate from Owen's judicial record to personal qualities, saying, &quot;I have heard my colleagues and some interest groups use very extreme language to describe Priscilla Owen.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>The Senate opened debate Monday on President Bush's contentious nomination of California State Supreme Court Justice Janice Rogers Brown to the federal bench, with Republicans praising her as a &quot;great talent&quot; while Democrats derided her as a conservative ideologue.<annotation scu-count="5" sum-count="7" sums="12,21,29,37,42,55,6"><scu uid="29" label="Brown's nomination debate opened" weight="2"/><scu uid="30" label="Brown's nomination debate opened on June 6, 2005" weight="1"/><scu uid="31" label="Republicans praised Brown's great talent" weight="1"/><scu uid="32" label="Democrats deemed Brown an extreme conservative ideologue" weight="1"/><scu uid="24" label="Janice Rogers Brown was a California Supreme Court Justice " weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Senators participating in the negotiations included Democrats Joseph Lieberman, Conn.; Ben Nelson, Neb.; Mark Pryor, Ark.; Robert Byrd, W.Va.; Mary Landrieu, La.; and Kenneth Salazar, Colo.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>She added, &quot;Packing the courts with people like this will set our country back.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>But the Democrat Bush defeated in the 2004 election, Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts, cautioned that the attempt by the Republican majority to change the Senate's rules in such an unusual way represents &quot;a dangerous time for our democracy.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>But while many white Republican senators praised Brown as a role model for African Americans, the only African American in the Senate, Barak Obama, D-Ill., voted against her and cautioned that Brown was not deserving of support &quot;just because she is a black woman.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050608.0153"><line>And the Senate voted Wednesday 67-32 to end debate, and foreclose any more filibustering, on the nomination to the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta of former Alabama State's Attorney William Pryor.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line><line>In a vote that had been blocked by a Democratic filibuster for the past two years, the Senate approved, 56-43, the appointment of Janice Rogers Brown to the powerful U.S. District Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="5" sums="0,10,16,36,42"><scu uid="41" label="Brown won confirmation 56-43" weight="3"/><scu uid="26" label="Brown's nomination had been stalled for 2 years" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>They also say GOP plans to change the filibuster rules will rend Senate traditions that protect the rights of the minority party.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., criticized Brown for taking an extremely limited view of government regulation in opinions that argued for rolling back the Social Security programs or zoning ordinances.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050608.0153"><line>Democrats have accepted the deal by the seven Republican and seven Democratic moderates because it preserves their right to use a filibuster against judicial nominees, though only in &quot;extraordinary circumstances.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., has revived a proposal to have the Senate Judiciary Committee, perhaps with the advice of an independent commission, provide the president with a list of potential nominees who would have bipartisan support.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Scott Shepard's e-mail address is sshepard@coxnews.com.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>How dare you bomb my city?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>Both sides are especially interested in the possibility of a Supreme Court vacancy this summer.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>&quot;The reason we're spending this whole week on judges is to demonstrate that we have returned, now, to where we were before the last Congress: fair up-or- down vote,&quot; Frist told reporters.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Vice President Dick Cheney is expected to preside over the session in his capacity as president of the Senate, in case his vote is needed to break a tie.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, R-Tenn., said he expected a confirmation vote on Pryor and the two Michigan nominees on Thursday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>A group of a dozen senators still held out hope Friday of averting the showdown by refusing to lend their votes to either side.</line><line>Since Republicans are in the majority, the objection would likely be rejected.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>The Senate also voted 67-32 to end debate on Bush's nomination of former Alabama attorney general William Pryor to a permanent seat on the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, based in Atlanta.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>It's mine.&quot;'</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>&quot;All we want is a vote - an up-or-down vote,' Frist said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Under one scenario, all would receive confirmation votes -- and presumably be seated on various appeals courts -- except Henry Saad of Michigan and William Myers of Idaho.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050524.0016"><line>&quot;In a Senate that is increasingly polarized, the bipartisan center held,&quot; Democratic Sen. Joseph Lieberman said Monday night.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>I think not,&quot; Reid said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>(Optional add end)</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>Brown's nomination is opposed by most black members of Congress, all of whom are Democrats.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050608.0153"><line>An outspoken conservative California judge criticized by Democrats as the most extreme of the president's judicial nominees won confirmation to the nation's most important appellate court Wednesday in a largely party-line Senate vote.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="1" sums="0"><scu uid="40" label="Brown won confirmation" weight="4"/><scu uid="42" label="Brown won confirmation on June 8, 2005" weight="3"/><scu uid="32" label="Democrats deemed Brown an extreme conservative ideologue" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Smith was the first of several Republican senators to cite Bush's victory in the 2004 presidential election as part of their reason for backing Frist's attempt to remove the filibuster from the Democrats' parliamentary arsenal before there are any battles over Supreme Court nominees.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050524.0295"><line>The breakthrough came only after 14 moderate senators reached a compromise over Bush's stalled judicial nominees on Monday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="16"><scu uid="9" label="Compromise agreement was reached by 14 senators" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Senate Republican and Democratic leaders have said they would accept no deal that violates their fundamental principles: for Republicans, that all judicial nominees be allowed confirmation votes that are decided by a simple majority; for Democrats, that no changes be made in the rules governing the filibuster.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>At a news conference, Democratic leader Harry Reid, D-Nev., accused Bush of entangling Congress in a conflict over judicial nominations by sending the Senate controversial nominees like Brown instead of consensus candidates.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>And not just on judges.</line><line>These statements are coming in many cases from many people who have not met her.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>But Frist is considering a procedure whereby the Senate's presiding officer, Vice President Dick Cheney, will rule that it is unconstitutional to filibuster a federal appeals court nomination, a ruling that could be upheld by at least 51 votes, ending debate and clearing the way for an up-or-down vote on the nominee.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>&quot;Shockingly unjust or unscrupulous - that's what Priscilla Owen is in the mind of the attorney general of the United States.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>While only a simple majority of 51 is required to confirm a judge, Senate rules require 60 votes to cut off debate and 67 votes to change the rules.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>Chief Justice William Rehnquist is 80 years old and suffering from cancer.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Since there are 44 Democrats and an independent who usually sides with them in the Senate, Republicans are expected to lose Tuesday's vote to end debate on Owen's nomination.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>The poll of 1,000 adults had a margin of error of 3 percentage points.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Isakson's comments on the Senate floor coincided with Frist's appearance at a news conference outside the Capitol with a group of black ministers, including Bishop Wellington Boone of The Father's House in Atlanta, in support of Brown's nomination to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="10"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>The court is often seen as a steppingstone to the Supreme Court.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Frist announced Thursday evening that the debate would resume Friday and that he would seek a vote to cut off the debate on Owen's nomination next Tuesday.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>Whether such conditions will be present after Pryor's floor vote is unclear, but Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, R-Tenn., has reiterated he will undertake special - and controversial - procedures to prevent any further filibusters of judicial nominees by the Democrats.</line><line>&quot;The American people will know we're doing the nation's business,&quot; added Frist.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>At stake is not just the nomination of Owen and several other Bush nominees to federal appellate courts but the president's ability to steer the entire federal judiciary in a more conservative direction with lifetime appointments to the nation's highest courts, including the Supreme Court where Chief Justice William Rehnquist is ailing with thyroid cancer.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>But both parties used another pending nomination, that of Janice Rogers Brown of California, an African American native of Alabama, to reach out to blacks in the fight over Senate procedures in addressing judicial nominations.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="1" label="Senate debated the issue of filibustering judicial nominations" weight="2"/><scu uid="4" label="Both parties used Brown's race, [African American], in their arguments" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>&quot;We would like nothing more than to remedy this problem.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>Four polls conducted last month found Congress with its lowest levels of public support in more than a decade.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>The controversy over confirming federal judges appears to have taken a toll on the public's approval of Congress.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>&quot;If Republicans roll back our rights in this chamber, there will be no check on their power.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>&quot;I do not rise for party.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>In addition, five of seven Bush nominees to the federal appellate courts would be given confirmation votes.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Senators from both parties filled the chamber all day with impassioned speeches about their constitutional duty to give the president &quot;advice and consent&quot; on judicial nominees.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="33"><scu uid="1" label="Senate debated the issue of filibustering judicial nominations" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>At that point, party leaders say they will conduct a series of maneuvers to establish a new procedure for confirming judges.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Activist groups on the left and right have grown increasingly intent on helping to shape the judiciary in recent years, as rulings on abortion, school prayer and other topics have stirred deep controversy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Optional adds follow.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>Republican Senate leaders wanted to strip Democrats of their right to filibuster judicial nominees until a compromise in late May among centrists in both parties cleared the way for votes on some of the disputed nominees, including Brown.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="6" label="Compromise agreement (CA) was reached " weight="4"/><scu uid="16" label="Nuclear option would have forced a change in filibuster rules" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>The debate on Owen's nomination to the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans began Wednesday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who blamed both parties for bringing the Senate to the brink of a political meltdown, decried such attempts at deal-making.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050524.0295"><line>The US Senate voted Tuesday to end debate on one of President George W. Bush's most controversial judicial nominees, averting a possible showdown.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="23"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>&quot;We've spent endless hours, endless days, too many weeks debating radical judges and Republican attempts to abuse power,&quot; Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid, D-Nev., said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Bush has nominated Owen to the New Orleans-based 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals and Brown to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia, widely viewed as second only to the Supreme Court in its impact on the American legal system.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="22"><scu uid="25" label="Brown's nomination was to the US District Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>It's what she will do to your life,&quot; Boxer said, referring to the public.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Meanwhile, Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., issued an apology for remarks on the Senate floor the previous day in which he invoked the name of Nazi dictator Adolf Hitler in criticizing Democrats.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Story can end here.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Even more intense action took place in small groups and closed meetings, as a half dozen GOP centrists, and an equal number of Democrats, tried to close a deal that would defuse the controversy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>The issue of how judicial nominations will be addressed in the Senate has taken on a new intensity with the prospect of several Supreme Court nominations in the final three and a half years of Bush's presidency, enough to solidify a conservative majority on the nine-member court for a generation.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>Before moving to Myers, &quot; I want to make sure the process works,&quot; Frist said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Still, a handful of moderates in both parties continued their talks to find a compromise short of the so-called &quot;nuclear option&quot; under consideration by Frist -- a parliamentary maneuver that would make it easier to confirm federal judges but also profoundly alter the way the Senate conducts its affairs.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>Scott Shepard's e-mail address is sshepard@coxnews.com.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Confirm the nominee, reject the nominee, but in the end, vote.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Seventy of Clinton's nominees were blocked through holds or other procedural maneuvers.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>Seven Democrats joined with seven Republicans last month and agreed not to continue the filibuster on Brown and several other judges, including Texas Supreme Court Justice Priscilla Owen, who was confirmed last month to the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="1" sums="22"><scu uid="45" label="CA - Oppose filibuster regarding Brown's confirmation" weight="4"/><scu uid="14" label="CA - Vote for cloture on three nominations " weight="3"/><scu uid="9" label="Compromise agreement was reached by 14 senators" weight="2"/></annotation></line><line>The motion to end debate, known as &quot;cloture,&quot; passed by a vote of 65-32, more than enough to clear the 60-vote threshold required.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050608.0153"><line>Brown became the second of three long-stalled judicial nominees who will win Senate votes because of a deal struck by 14 moderate senators to avert a partisan showdown over the Democrats' filibusters of the president's judge nominees.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="49"><scu uid="9" label="Compromise agreement was reached by 14 senators" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>&quot;Against this background of bitter and angry recriminations, with each party serially trumpeting the other party to get even or really to dominate, the Senate now faces dual threats&quot; -- the filibuster and the &quot;nuclear&quot; option, Specter said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Sen. Johnny Isakson, R-Ga., recalled the infamous filibusters of Southern segregationists in the 1960s who tried to block passage of major civil rights legislation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>And the Senate vote confirming Brown produced a flood of responses from interest groups reflecting that political divide.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Their power will be unchecked on Supreme Court nominees, the president's nominees in general and legislation like Social Security privatization.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>&quot;This is a controversy, but not a crisis,&quot; Cornyn said.</line><line>Sen. Lamar Alexander, R-Tenn., said Friday that perhaps 80 percent of senators, while unwilling to buck party leaders by signing onto the compromise, nonetheless hoped it succeeds.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Myers, aides said, was a lower priority to Republican conservatives determined to secure confirmations for Priscilla Owen of Texas, Janice Rogers Brown of California and William Pryor Jr. of Alabama.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,3"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>The motion schedules for Tuesday the long-anticipated showdown over whether Democrats have the right to use the parliamentary tactic known as the filibuster to block President Bush's judicial nominations.</line><line>The filibuster is the right of senators to engage in extended debate on an issue.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>&quot;Judicial nominees with the support of a majority of senators deserve up-or-down votes on this floor...</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Both votes would require a simple majority of 51.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>The Republicans want to eliminate the filibuster for judicial nominees, making it possible to approve judges with 51 votes -- an approach known as the &quot;nuclear option&quot; because of the potential impact on Senate comity.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>Frist said they were not on the Senate calendar for the near future.</line><line>During debate Tuesday, Democrats urged their Republican colleagues to abandon the party's position and vote against Brown, whom they repeatedly described as &quot;out of the mainstream.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>But immediately after Wednesday's votes, Frist said the Senate had &quot;broken the impasse&quot; on judicial nominees and, after confirmation votes on Pryor and a handful of non-controversial pending nominations, the Senate will begin work on energy legislation, probably next week.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>The filibuster rarely figured in judicial fights until Bush's first term, when Democrats used it to keep 10 appellate court nominees from having confirmation votes.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Bush renominated seven of them, including Owen and California Supreme Court Justice Janice Rogers Brown.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="13,25"><scu uid="24" label="Janice Rogers Brown was a California Supreme Court Justice " weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Other Republican senators simply want to proceed with a vote on changing the rules on filibustering judicial nominations because, win or lose, the matter would be put to rest.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>Seven of the 10 Democrats who voted to end debate on Brown were signers of the moderates' pact: Sen. Robert Byrd of West Virginia, Sen. Daniel K. Inouye of Hawaii, Sen. Mary Landrieu of Louisiana, Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut, Sen. Ben Nelson of Nebraska, Sen. Mark Pryor of Arkansas, and Sen. Ken Salazar of Colorado.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050608.0153"><line>&quot;Now the question is what do the Democrats get out of this agreement?&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>But Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., who met with Owen during the nominee's courtesy visits with senators Tuesday, replied that &quot;I couldn't agree more she was a lovely person, but this is not a debate about a lovely person - this is a debate about a record... and whether that record merits appointing someone to a lifetime appointment.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>The agreement, while granting a floor vote to long-stalled Bush judicial nominees Brown, Pryor and Priscilla Owen, confirmed to a seat on the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, also preserved the right of the Democratic minority to filibuster future nominees under undefined &quot;extraordinary conditions.&quot;<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="16,48"><scu uid="40" label="Brown won confirmation" weight="4"/><scu uid="25" label="Brown's nomination was to the US District Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Democrats, for instance, have threatened to stall much of the chamber's business if the ban is adopted.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>&quot;Believe me, we know well that there are too few African Americans and too few women on the courts,&quot; said McDonald, pastor of the First Iconium Baptist Church in Atlanta.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050608.0153"><line>Late last month, the long-delayed nomination of Texas state judge Priscilla Owen to the 5th Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans was approved in the Senate under the deal.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050524.0295"><line>Republicans have threatened to strip Democrats of their right to filibuster, or make an extended debate for delaying legislative action.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>&quot;I would hope that Republican senators would look at Janice Rogers Brown for what she really is,&quot; Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid, D-Nev., told reporters after the vote.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="37,42,6"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050608.0153"><line>&quot;They are getting what they want,&quot; said Carl Tobias, a law professor at the University of Richmond in Virginia.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Republicans filed a motion Friday to end debate on the nomination of Texas Supreme Court Justice Priscilla Owen to the federal bench, a move starting the countdown to the so-called nuclear option.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="23"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>&quot;Send a message that extremists are unacceptable to the federal judiciary,&quot; Rep. Melvin Watt, D-N.C., said in a statement.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050524.0295"><line>Bush nominated Owen to a seat on the 5th US Circuit Court of Appeals in his first term, but the nomination has been blocked four times by Democratic filibusters.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="43"><scu uid="18" label="Pricilla Owen was a nominee for U.S. Appeals Court 5th Circuit" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0145"><line>Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid, D-Nev., showing support for the Congressional Black Caucus, noted that &quot;our nation's judges and courts have often been the last resort for minorities seeking redress from inadequate or unfair laws&quot; but that could change if the Democrats can't block &quot;radical&quot; judges.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>In return, the six GOP signers would agree to vote against efforts to ban judicial filibusters, the aides said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>The fight over the nominees has not only dominated the work of the Senate but has deepened the political divide in the nation's capital because of the potential the president has to reshape the federal government in his conservative image through such lifetime appointments.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>Democrats, even as they took note of the agreement to end the filibuster of Brown, urged senators to vote against her confirmation, based on her legal record.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050520.0142"><line>Senators would then vote on whether to table, or reject, the Democratic objection.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050524.0016"><line>The two-page memorandum of agreement said it is &quot;based upon mutual trust and confidence.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>&quot;Mainstream?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>Pryor has been serving on the court under a temporary appointment since February 2004.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="10"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050606.0128"><line>&quot;Both in her court decisions and in her many writings, Ms. Brown rejects the civil rights remedies Congress has enacted and that the courts have approved... and believes that parts of... the 1964 Civil Rights Act are unconstitutional,&quot; Rep. Melvin L. Watt, D-N.C., chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus, said in a statement.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>Democrats denounced his remarks.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050607.0113"><line>It's going to work with the Michigan judges...And then we'll just proceed down the line in regular order.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>&quot;Some of them wouldn't make it,&quot; Graham said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050524.0016"><line>Under the terms, Democrats would agree to oppose any attempt to filibuster _ and thus block final votes _ on the confirmation of Priscilla Owen, Janice Rogers Brown and William Pryor.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="40"><scu uid="14" label="CA - Vote for cloture on three nominations " weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050518.0144"><line>I rise for principle,&quot; Frist said moments after calling up Owen's nomination to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 5th Circuit.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050518.0167"><line>Currently, it takes 60 votes to stop a filibuster, a form of extended debate that dates back to the 1850s.</line><line>Likewise, Brown, who was first nominated by Bush in 2003, has been blocked by the Democrats on four separate occasions.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050608.0132"><line>But her Republican supporters have countered that she is a model of judicial restraint, and in nearly every speech from the Senate floor in recent weeks, they have lauded her rise from a poor childhood in segregated Alabama to prominence as a judge.</line></document></collection>